In the Glowstick world, it is not immediately easy to use rooms and space as a method of editing parts. This is because although parts can contain a large number of subparts (especially when considering the entire tree), having to scale the parent part to be larger than the subpart goes against the design of the part: parts should all feel equal in nature, despite their constituents.

In a world where dimension is completely linear requires a massive change in presentation due purely to scaling the hierarchy.

To resolve this, the system will take inspiration from the TARDIS (Time and Relative Dimension in Space) from Doctor Who. In other words, parts will always be the same size: they will occupy a certain cube. They will be just big enough to climb inside. Once inside, they will be bigger on the inside.

This particular TARDIS presentation will allow parts to be filled with other parts on the inside, each of which can be entered and seen to be bigger on the inside.

Parts can be exactly the size they need to be to comfortably present an explorable level that is completely dedicated to the part itself, rather than having the size be locked to some fixed size for every part. This could involve implementing a mesh onto every single part, including the framework's own parts.

Potentially, a separation can be established between a project's parts and the framework's parts. As a first pass - and because the Glowstick game is part of the Demo Ecosystem and not the framework - it might make sense to only flesh out the meshes for the Demo Ecosystem.